<subSubSection lastPageId="45" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="key">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,1551,2022]" box="[151,1435,1551,1574]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">1 Palpi mostly pale setose, black setae usually sparse, at most apical 1/4–1/3 black setose........................................... 2</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,1551,2022]" box="[151,1435,1583,1606]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">- Palpi mostly black setose, at least apical 1/2 black setose............................................................................................ 3</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,1551,2022]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
2 Palpi with several black setae on apical 1/4–1/3; pleuron mostly black setose dorsally; costal margin slightly to moderately dilated; abdominal tergites 6–7 white tomentose; sternites 7–8 often with long yellowish setae apically, extending beyond base of terminalia; apical margin of sternite 8 produced medially; gonocoxa entirely black setose, terminalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[370,509,1711,1734]" captionStart="FIGURES 97–102" captionStartId="47.[151,269,1954,1978]" captionTargetBox="[157,1423,385,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@47.[151,1436,310,1930]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 97–102. Efferia forbesi (Curran). Male terminalia: 97. Lateral view, lateral view: 98. Gonostylus; 99. Phallus; and 100. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia: 101. Ovipositor; 102. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455848/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Figs. 97–100</figureCitation>
<emphasis box="[513,1259,1712,1735]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">................................................................................................................</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Curran)" authorityName="Mystax" baseAuthorityName="Curran" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[1264,1435,1711,1735]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="forbesi">
<emphasis box="[1264,1338,1712,1735]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">forbesi</emphasis>
(Curran)
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,1551,2022]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
- Palpi pale setose, usually only 1–3 black setae apically; pleuron mostly pale setose dorsally, anepisternum with sparse black setae dorsally and posteriorly; costal margin not dilated; abdominal tergites 6–7 entirely and 5 apically white tomentose; sternites 7–8 without unusually long yellowish setae apically; apical margin of sternite 8 straight, not produced medially; gonocoxa black setose usually bordered by sparse pale setae basally, terminalia as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 116–121" captionStartId="56.[151,270,1611,1635]" captionTargetBox="[242,1366,181,1551]" captionTargetId="figure@56.[236,1370,126,1650]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 116–121. Efferia portoricensis (Hine). Male terminalia, lateral view: 116. Intact, left side; 117. Gonostylus; 118.Phallus; and 119. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia, lateral view: 120. Ovipositor; 121. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455856/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Figs. 116–119</figureCitation>
<emphasis box="[293,1206,1872,1895]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">.........................................................................................................................................</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Hine)" authorityName="Post" baseAuthorityName="Hine" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[1212,1429,1871,1895]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="portoricensis">
<emphasis box="[1212,1353,1872,1895]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">portoricensis</emphasis>
(Hine)
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,1551,2022]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
3 Face with mostly or entirely black vestiture; epandrium short and wide, 2–2.5 times as long as wide, truncate dorsally; sternite 8 produced with apical setae usually dense, concealing gonocoxa basally; gonocoxal setae sparse posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[292,439,1967,1990]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–115" captionStartId="52.[151,275,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[164,1432,272,1867]" captionTargetId="figure@52.[151,1436,271,1877]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURES 110–115. Efferia nigrimystacea (Macquart) Male terminalia, lateral view: 110. Intact, left side; 111. Gonostylus; 112. Phallus; and 113. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia, lateral view: 114. Ovipositor; 115. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455854/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Figs. 110–113</figureCitation>
)......................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Macquart)" authorityName="Macquart" box="[1158,1436,1967,1991]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrimystacea">
<emphasis box="[1158,1309,1968,1991]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">nigrimystacea</emphasis>
(Macquart)
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,1551,2022]" box="[151,1436,1999,2022]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">- Face with mixed black and pale vestiture medially or dorsally, pale vestiture laterally and ventrally; epandrium lon-</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,152,463]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
ger and narrower, 3 times as long as wide, apex not truncate dorsally; sternite 8 not strongly produced and without dense apical setae, setae never concealing gonocoxa basally; gonocoxal setae dense posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[1226,1328,184,207]" captionStart="FIGURES 103–108" captionStartId="50.[151,271,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,253,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@50.[151,1436,253,1878]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 103–108. Efferia montensis sp. nov. Male terminalia, lateral view: 103. Intact, left side; 104. Gonostylus; 105. Phallus; and 106. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia, lateral view: 107. Ovipositor; 108. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455850/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs. 103</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1340,1381,184,207]" captionStart="FIGURES 122–127" captionStartId="58.[151,269,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[186,1410,309,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@58.[169,1413,299,1854]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURES 122–127. Efferia stylata (Fabricius). Male terminalia: 122. Lateral view, lateral view: 123. Gonostylus; 124. Phallus; and 125. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia: 126. Ovipositor; 127. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455858/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">122</figureCitation>
) ... 4
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,152,463]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
4 Face, frons, and pro- and mesothoracic femora mostly or entirely golden yellow setose; postocular bristles yellow; scutum and basal 4 abdominal segments golden brownish-yellow tomentose; wing only slightly dilated; segments 5–7 white tomentose; epandrium with 2 spike-like processes dorsally; gonostylus wide apically; terminalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[199,351,312,335]" captionStart="FIGURES 103–108" captionStartId="50.[151,271,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,253,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@50.[151,1436,253,1878]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURES 103–108. Efferia montensis sp. nov. Male terminalia, lateral view: 103. Intact, left side; 104. Gonostylus; 105. Phallus; and 106. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia, lateral view: 107. Ovipositor; 108. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455850/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs. 103–106</figureCitation>
<emphasis box="[353,1344,312,335]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
.................................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Perez-Gelabert" authorityYear="2009" box="[1237,1344,312,335]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montensis" status="sp. nov.">montensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1351,1436,311,335]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1351,1436,311,335]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,152,463]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,160,343,367]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">-</emphasis>
Face, frons and pro- and mesothoracic femora mostly or entirely white setose; postocular bristles black; scutum and basal 4 abdominal segments yellowish-gray tomentose; usually only segments 6–7 entirely and part of tergite 5 white tomentose, rarely 5–7 white tomentose; epandrium simple dorsally, spike-like processes absent; gonostylus narrow, blade-like apically; terminalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[669,821,440,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 122–127" captionStartId="58.[151,269,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[186,1410,309,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@58.[169,1413,299,1854]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURES 122–127. Efferia stylata (Fabricius). Male terminalia: 122. Lateral view, lateral view: 123. Gonostylus; 124. Phallus; and 125. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia: 126. Ovipositor; 127. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455858/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs. 122–125</figureCitation>
<emphasis box="[826,1239,440,463]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">..............................................................</emphasis>
